“What is autism?
Autism is a lifelong developmental disability that affects how people perceive the world and interact with others.”

@MsVeruca - Neurodivergent and autistic don’t mean the same thing. You can be neurodivergent and not autistic.
- Not all autistic people have superpowers or amazing gifts. 

If you want informed opinions try asking actual autistic people. You can use the hashtag #AskingAutistics.  4/4

@MsVeruca - Just because an autistic person may appear highly capable, this does not mean they are not also disabled in some ways.
- Most autistic people prefer to be called “autistic” rather than “with autism”.
- “Autistic” is not an outdated or offensive term. 3/

@MsVeruca - Terms like mild/severe and high/low functioning are outdated and unhelpful.
- Non-verbal does not mean someone is unintelligent or that they don’t understand.
- Asperger’s is autism. 2/

@MsVeruca I am disappointed at how ignorant (if well-meaning) some of the replies to this have been. To clear a few things up:

- No, we are not all “somewhere on the spectrum” or “a little bit autistic”.
- The autism spectrum is not linear so it doesn’t have “ends”.  1/

